{"title_page": "Australian Red Cross Lifeblood", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\nThe '''Australian Red Cross Lifeblood'''  is a branch of the [[Australian Red Cross]]. It is the body primarily responsible for [[blood donation]] and related services in Australia.  Australian Red Cross Blood Service employs around 3,700 employees across scientific, medical and support services, processing over half a million non-remunerated blood donors each year.\n\nThe Blood Service is funded by the state and federal governments of Australia and is a division of Australian Red Cross. It had been known for many years as the '''Australian Red Cross Blood Service''', but on 15 November 2019 it was renamed Australian Red Cross Lifeblood.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.donateblood.com.au/about | title=About | publisher=Australian Red Cross Lifeblood | quote=On 15 November 2019 we changed from Australian Red Cross Blood Service to Australian Red Cross Lifeblood. <!--Quoting because this looks like a temporary placement at the top of the website. The text was present as of 10 December 2019.-->| accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Red Cross's Australian blood services were initially managed by state-level organisations.  [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]'s Blood Transfusion Service was founded in 1929, and by 1941 each state had its own Organ Transfusion Service. Also in 1941, the National Emergency Blood Transfusion Service (later the National Blood Transfusion Committee) was formed to coordinate the state groups. In 1945, the Red Cross took over blood and serum preparation units established by the [[Australian Army]].\n\nIn 1995, a government report recommended the foundation of a separate national structure, and the ARCBS was formed in 1996, encompassing the old state and territory blood donation/transfusion services.\n\n==Relationship with CSL==\nAustralian Red Cross Lifeblood and its predecessors had a long-standing relationship with the [[CSL Limited|Commonwealth Serum Laboratories]] (CSL), a government medical body founded in 1916. The Red Cross supplied CSL with donated blood for use in research and manufacture of medical products (e.g. serum for transfusion).\n\nIn 1994, CSL was privatised, becoming CSL Limited. The ARCBS continued to supply CSL with donated blood.\n\n==Infectious diseases==\nBlood donated in Australia has been tested for [[Hepatitis B]] since 1972, [[HIV]]-1 since 1985, [[Hepatitis C]] since 1990, HIV-2 since 1992/3, and [[Human T-lymphotropic virus|HTLV-1]] since 1993.\n\nAs with other blood transfusion services, the ARCBS has had to strike a balance between protecting blood recipients against infection, and accepting enough donors to maintain an adequate supply of blood. This has led to debate over which categories of potential donors should be excluded. For example, to protect against [[Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease|CJD]], the ARCBS now refuses donations from anybody who lived in the [[United Kingdom]] for a total of six months or more between 1980 and 1996.\n\nIn 2003, a federal government report found that despite the introduction of Hepatitis C screening from February 1990, infected donors were told to keep donating until July of that same year; a total of 20,000 people were estimated to have been infected with Hepatitis C via blood products. Some infected blood was given to CSL and may have been used in thousands of CSL products, although it has not been shown that any of these products caused infection in the recipients.<ref>http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/05/14/1052885298025.html</ref>\n\nThe service has a policy of barring [[Men who have sex with men|men who have had sex with men (MSM)]] during the previous twelve months from donating blood (an earlier policy had excluded any men who had had sex with other men since 1980, regardless of time elapsed). This has been the source of ongoing controversy, with a case (in 2008) referred to the Tasmanian Anti-Discrimination Commission.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/15/2337087.htm Gay safe sex poses low risk to blood supply, tribunal hears</ref> People who have engaged in heterosexual or female-to-female sex during the past 12 months are allowed to give blood. Female-to-female transmission is considered by the [[Centers for Disease Control]] to be rare.<ref>http://www.thebody.com/cdc/femtrans.html Female-to-Female Transmission of HIV CDC National AIDS Hotline Training Bulletin #139</ref> As well as deferring blood donations from MSM, other categories of sexual activity can also result in a 12-month deferral, such as sex with a [[prostitute]] or having a partner who has tested positive to hepatitis B or C.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donateblood.com.au/Donor/guide/eligible.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060819101820/http://www.donateblood.com.au/Donor/guide/eligible.asp |archivedate=2006-08-19 }} Australian Red Cross Blood Donor Eligibility</ref>\n\nIn 2014, gay men again requested that the Australian Red Cross Blood Service permit them to donate blood.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob|last=Stott|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/blood-donation-rules-continue-to-exclude-healthy-donors/story-fneuz9ev-1226922550697 |title=Blood donation rules continue to exclude healthy donors |work=[[News Corp Australia|News Ltd]]|date=19 May 2014|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donateblood.com.au/faq#faq_294 |title=Frequently Asked Questions |work=Australian Red Cross Blood Service|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>  The Red Cross, in noting their concern, said they were receptive to a reduction in the current deferral period from 12 to 6 months. However, the Australian [[Therapeutic Goods Administration]] has rejected their submission on this issue, arguing that there would be a greater risk of HIV without a significant increase in blood supply.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tga.gov.au/sites/default/files/foi-322-1415-01.pdf |title=TGA response to proposal for changes to blood donor deferral guidelines |accessdate =2 March 2017}}</ref> The Red Cross say they do not defer based on sexuality or relationships, but rather on sexual activity and for this reason it is not possible to deal with MSM on an individual basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.donateblood.com.au/media-centre/news/national/fact-finder-our-response-to-newscomaus-gay-blood-donation-article |title=Fact Finder: Our response to news.com.au's gay blood donation article |work=Australian Red Cross Blood Service |date=19 May 2014 |accessdate=8 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608103218/http://www.donateblood.com.au/media-centre/news/national/fact-finder-our-response-to-newscomaus-gay-blood-donation-article |archivedate=8 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[MSM blood donor controversy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.lifeblood.com.au/ Australian Red Cross Lifeblood website]\n*[http://www.transfusion.com.au/ Red Cross transfusion medicine website for health professionals]\n*[https://www.worktheworld.com.au/blood-and-organ-donation-myths-and-facts/ Blood and Organ Donation Myths and Facts]\n[[Category:Blood donation]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\nThe '''Australian Red Cross Lifeblood'''  is a branch of the [[Australian Red Cross]]. It is the body primarily responsible for [[blood donation]] and related services in Australia.  Australian Red Cross Blood Service employs around 3,700 employees across scientific, medical and support services, processing over half a million non-remunerated blood donors each year.\n\nThe Blood Service is funded by the state and federal governments of Australia and is a division of Australian Red Cross. It had been known for many years as the '''Australian Red Cross Blood Service''', but on 15 November 2019 it was renamed Australian Red Cross Lifeblood.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.donateblood.com.au/about | title=About | publisher=Australian Red Cross Lifeblood | quote=On 15 November 2019 we changed from Australian Red Cross Blood Service to Australian Red Cross Lifeblood. <!--Quoting because this looks like a temporary placement at the top of the website. The text was present as of 10 December 2019.-->| accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Red Cross's Australian blood services were initially managed by state-level organisations.  [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]'s Blood Transfusion Service was founded in 1929, and by 1941 each state had its own Organ Transfusion Service. Also in 1941, the National Emergency Blood Transfusion Service (later the National Blood Transfusion Committee) was formed to coordinate the state groups. In 1945, the Red Cross took over blood and serum preparation units established by the [[Australian Army]].\n\nIn 1995, a government report recommended the foundation of a separate national structure, and the ARCBS was formed in 1996, encompassing the old state and territory blood donation/transfusion services.\n\n==Relationship with CSL==\nAustralian Red Cross Lifeblood and its predecessors had a long-standing relationship with the [[CSL Limited|Commonwealth Serum Laboratories]] (CSL), a government medical body founded in 1916. The Red Cross supplied CSL with donated blood for use in research and manufacture of medical products (e.g. serum for transfusion).\n\nIn 1994, CSL was privatised, becoming CSL Limited. The ARCBS continued to supply CSL with donated blood.\n\n==Infectious diseases==\nBlood donated in Australia has been tested for [[Hepatitis B]] since 1972, [[HIV]]-1 since 1985, [[Hepatitis C]] since 1990, HIV-2 since 1992/3, and [[Human T-lymphotropic virus|HTLV-1]] since 1993.\n\nAs with other blood transfusio