h deferral, such as sex with a [[prostitute]] or having a partner who has tested positive to hepatitis B or C.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donateblood.com.au/Donor/guide/eligible.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060819101820/http://www.donateblood.com.au/Donor/guide/eligible.asp |archivedate=2006-08-19 }} Australian Red Cross Blood Donor Eligibility</ref>\n\nIn 2014, gay men again requested that the Australian Red Cross Blood Service permit them to donate blood.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob|last=Stott|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/blood-donation-rules-continue-to-exclude-healthy-donors/story-fneuz9ev-1226922550697 |title=Blood donation rules continue to exclude healthy donors |work=[[News Corp Australia|News Ltd]]|date=19 May 2014|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donateblood.com.au/faq#faq_294 |title=Frequently Asked Questions |work=Australian Red Cross Blood Service|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>  The Red Cross, in noting their concern, said they were receptive to a reduction in the current deferral period from 12 to 6 months. However, the Australian [[Therapeutic Goods Administration]] has rejected their submission on this issue, arguing that there would be a greater risk of HIV without a significant increase in blood supply.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tga.gov.au/sites/default/files/foi-322-1415-01.pdf |title=TGA response to proposal for changes to blood donor deferral guidelines |accessdate =2 March 2017}}</ref> The Red Cross say they do not defer based on sexuality or relationships, but rather on sexual activity and for this reason it is not possible to deal with MSM on an individual basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.donateblood.com.au/media-centre/news/national/fact-finder-our-response-to-newscomaus-gay-blood-donation-article |title=Fact Finder: Our response to news.com.au's gay blood donation article |work=Australian Red Cross Blood Servi